1 Learning Outcomes

  • Open up a terminal window in R Studio.
  • Execute basic shell commands to navigate among directories and manipulate files.

1.1 References

  • Chapter 4 of Git for Scientists.

2 The Terminal Window

  • A terminal Window provides access to a command line where we can enter commands to the system through a shell layer.

  • The easiest way to open a terminal window is within R Studio with Tools > Terminal > New Terminal

  • The terminal window should look like this:


  • The path before the dollar sign is the working directory of the terminal window, not Rs working directory. Its where the shell will look as the starting point for all commands and files.

  • The tilde or twiddle, ~, is shorthand for the home directory. Each computer has a home directory that is the default directory for Git - usually your Users/username directory.

2.1 The Command Line

  • The command line is like the R command prompt: you insert code, hit enter, and then the computer executes your command.

    • Other words for command line: shell, terminal, command line interface (cli), and console.
    • These terms are technically slightly different.

  • All commands get placed after the dollar sign.

  • However, instead of typing R code, you type Shell Script.

  • In this class, we will use the command line primarily for two things:

    • Moving around your file system.
    • Running git commands.

3 Bash (the Bourne-Again SHell)

  • There are many types of shells, each with their own scripting language.

  • We will use the [Bash scripting language ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bash_(Unix_shell%29) for this class.

  • A huge difference between R and Bash is how commands/functions are called.

    • R: f(x, y = 1)
    • Bash: f x --y=1
    • Arguments that are flags use only one dash, like f x -g would incorporate the g flag.
    • Well see this in git

  • A similarity is Bash is also case sensitive on commands and names e.g., cd no CD

  • If you are using Linux or Mac, then you can keep going.

  • If you are using Windows, you need to first download and install git (and thus git bash) from here: http://git-scm.com/download/win.

    • You might need to restart R Studio if you are already running it.

3.1 Bash Commands for Navigating the Directory Structure:

  • Changing the Bash terminal window working directory is done by using Bash commands to navigate (move) to another directory, e.g., where you have files of interest.

  • pwd: Print working directory. Show the current working directory. This is like getwd() in R.

    pwd
    ## /Users/rressler/OneDrive - american.edu/Courses/STAT-413-613/Lectures_All_Summer/01_git_github

  • ls: List the current files and folders in a directory.

    ls
    ## 01a_basic_bash.Rmd
## 01a_basic_bash.html
## 01b_git_github.Rmd
## Resources
## git_github_citations.bib
## graphics
## life_exp
## life_exp_analysis.Rmd

  • cd: Change directories. This is like setwd() in R. As when we specified relative paths in R, using two periods means move back (up) a folder and/" means move down a folder: cd ../foldername".

    cd ../
pwd
    ## /Users/rressler/OneDrive - american.edu/Courses/STAT-413-613/Lectures_All_Summer

  • If you use cd without specifying a folder to move to, it will move the working directory to the home directory.

    cd
pwd
    ## /Users/rressler

  • . is shorthand for the current working directory

  • You can combine the move up and move down arguments to navigate several layers up and/or down in one command.

  • As an example, Im going to move from the home directory back to my course directory: /OneDrive\ -\ american.edu/Courses/STAT-413-613.

    • As a shortcut, you can type a letter then hit the tab key and Bash will fill in valid letters to the point of ambiguity (if there is one). This can save a lot of typing errors.
      • Note: It automatically escapes any spaces in the directory names by putting a backslash \ in front of them.
      cd ./OneDrive\ -\ american.edu/Courses/STAT-413-613/

  • man: Read the manual of a command. Just like help() in R.

    man ls

    • This will open up the man page of ls. You can scroll through this page using the up and down arrows.

    • Exit this page by typing q.

    • This wont work for Git Bash (for Windows users). Instead, youll need to type

          ls --help

3.2 Bash Commands for Managing Files and Directories

  • cp: Copy a file in your working directory with cp filename newfilename. You can add relative paths to either argument.

    cp 01_basic_bash.html hellobash.html
ls
    ## cp: 01_basic_bash.html: No such file or directory
## 01a_basic_bash.Rmd
## 01a_basic_bash.html
## 01b_git_github.Rmd
## Resources
## git_github_citations.bib
## graphics
## life_exp
## life_exp_analysis.Rmd

  • mv: Move/rename a file.

    mv hellobash.html goodbyebash.html
ls
    ## mv: rename hellobash.html to goodbyebash.html: No such file or directory
## 01a_basic_bash.Rmd
## 01a_basic_bash.html
## 01b_git_github.Rmd
## Resources
## git_github_citations.bib
## graphics
## life_exp
## life_exp_analysis.Rmd

  • rm: Remove a file.

    rm goodbyebash.html
ls
    ## rm: goodbyebash.html: No such file or directory
## 01a_basic_bash.Rmd
## 01a_basic_bash.html
## 01b_git_github.Rmd
## Resources
## git_github_citations.bib
## graphics
## life_exp
## life_exp_analysis.Rmd

  • mkdir: Make a directory/folder.

    mkdir tempdir
ls
    ## 01a_basic_bash.Rmd
## 01a_basic_bash.html
## 01b_git_github.Rmd
## Resources
## git_github_citations.bib
## graphics
## life_exp
## life_exp_analysis.Rmd
## tempdir

  • rmdir: Remove a directory/folder.

    rmdir tempdir
ls
    ## 01a_basic_bash.Rmd
## 01a_basic_bash.html
## 01b_git_github.Rmd
## Resources
## git_github_citations.bib
## graphics
## life_exp
## life_exp_analysis.Rmd

  • Terminus is a game you can play for more practice at navigating using Bash.
